paragraphs.text:
%md
## Auto Insurance Claims Fraud - Unsupervised Learning

#### Nearly one of 10 Americans would commit insurance fraud if they knew they could get away with it. Nearly one of four Americans say it’s ok to defraud insurers.   About one in 10 people agree it’s ok to submit claims for items that aren’t lost or damaged, or for personal injuries that didn’t occur. Two of five people are “not very likely” or “not likely at all” to report someone who ripped of an insurer.  Accenture Ltd.(2003)   Nearly three of 10 Americans (29 percent) wouldn't report insurance scams committed by someone they know.  Progressive Insurance (2001)


#### This notebook shows how to "flag" anomalous insurance claims using an unsupervised learning algorithm (1-Class Support Vector Machine).  The notebook first builds a 1-Class SVM model and then applies the model to flag unusual or suspicious auto insurance claims .   The anomaly detection model can also be applied to “score” new records.  The entire machine learning methodology runs inside the ADW.

#### By Charlie Berger, updated March 2021

Auto Insurance Claims Fraud - Unsupervised Learning

Nearly one of 10 Americans would commit insurance fraud if they knew they could get away with it. Nearly one of four Americans say it’s ok to defraud insurers. About one in 10 people agree it’s ok to submit claims for items that aren’t lost or damaged, or for personal injuries that didn’t occur. Two of five people are “not very likely” or “not likely at all” to report someone who ripped of an insurer. Accenture Ltd.(2003) Nearly three of 10 Americans (29 percent) wouldn't report insurance scams committed by someone they know. Progressive Insurance (2001)

This notebook shows how to “flag” anomalous insurance claims using an unsupervised learning algorithm (1-Class Support Vector Machine). The notebook first builds a 1-Class SVM model and then applies the model to flag unusual or suspicious auto insurance claims . The anomaly detection model can also be applied to “score” new records. The entire machine learning methodology runs inside the ADW.

By Charlie Berger, updated March 2021

%md 
![tiny arrow](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/options/advanced-analytics/autoinsurancepic60-5434493.jpg "tiny arrow")

%md

## Business Problem

#### We want to sift through our recent automobile insurance claims looking for anomalies that are suscicious and potentially fraudulent insurance claims.   We will use an unsupervised learning Oracle Machine Learning 1-class Support Vector Machine algorithm build and apply models on this "unlabeled" data to identify the most suspicious claims (e.g. top 1-2%) for further investigation by auto insurance claims investigators who will assign "labels" Fraudfound Yes/No for further supervised OML learning predictive models.

paragraphs.title: Display all Customers in Probability of Being Anomalous in Descending Order

%sql

(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,

(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '0' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS0
))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Display Suspicious Claims by AGE of PolicyHolder
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '0' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS0
))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Display Suspicious Claims by AGE of PolicyHolder
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '1' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS0
))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Show the Top 5 Most Suspicious Customers
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '0' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS0
))
where rnk <= 5
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Display Suspicious Claims by Number of Cars in Accident and Witnesses Present or Not
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '0' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS0
))

paragraphs.title: Create table SUSPICIOUS_CLAIMS for investigation using APEX or Oracle Analytics Cloud
paragraphs.text:
%sql

CREATE TABLE SUSPICIOUS_CLAIMS AS 
  SELECT * FROM
  (select POLICYNUMBER, 
  AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, 
  SEX, 
  MARITALSTATUS,
  DEDUCTIBLE, 
  AGEOFVEHICLE, 
  WEEKOFMONTHCLAIMED, 
  BASEPOLICY, 
  ADDRESSCHANGECLAIM, 
  DAYSPOLICYCLAIM, 
  DRIVERRATING, 
  POLICEREPORTFILED, 
  PASTNUMBEROFCLAIMS, 
  WEEKOFMONTH, 
  WITNESSPRESENT, 
  DAYOFWEEKCLAIMED, 
  FRAUDFOUND, 
  MONTHCLAIMED, 
  MAKE, 
  REPNUMBER, 
  NUMBEROFCARS, 
  DAYSPOLICYACCIDENT, 
  FAULT, 
  NUMBEROFSUPPLIMENTS, 
  ACCIDENTAREA, 
  VEHICLEPRICE, 
  VEHICLECATEGORY, 
  PREDICTIONDETAILS,
  AGENTTYPE, 
  round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk 
      from
  (select POLICYNUMBER, 
  AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, 
  SEX, MARITALSTATUS, 
  DEDUCTIBLE, 
  AGEOFVEHICLE, 
  WEEKOFMONTHCLAIMED,
  BASEPOLICY, ADDRESSCHANGECLAIM, DAYSPOLICYCLAIM, DRIVERRATING, POLICEREPORTFILED, PASTNUMBEROFCLAIMS, WEEKOFMONTH, WITNESSPRESENT, DAYOFWEEKCLAIMED, FRAUDFOUND, MONTHCLAIMED, MAKE, REPNUMBER, NUMBEROFCARS, DAYSPOLICYACCIDENT, FAULT, NUMBEROFSUPPLIMENTS, ACCIDENTAREA, VEHICLEPRICE, VEHICLECATEGORY, AGENTTYPE, prediction_probability(CLAIMSMODEL, '0' using *) prob_fraud, PREDICTION_DETAILS("CLAIMSMODEL", '0', 5 ABS USING *) "PREDICTIONDETAILS" 
   from CLAIMS
  ))
order by percent_fraud desc;
